sponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis description matches an \u003Cstrong\u003Eepithelial cast\u003C/strong\u003E, which contains intact renal tubular epithelial cells trapped within a protein matrix. These casts indicate acute tubular injury or necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyaline casts\u003C/strong\u003E consist of only protein without cellular elements and appear clear and transparent\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranular casts\u003C/strong\u003E contain degraded cellular debris appearing as fine or coarse granules without intact cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERed blood cell casts\u003C/strong\u003E contain intact erythrocytes and indicate glomerular bleeding\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWaxy casts\u003C/strong\u003E appear broad, opaque and rigid, typically seen in chronic kidney disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of recognisable epithelial cells with visible nuclei within the cast matrix is diagnostic of epithelial casts. These casts are important indicators of acute tubular injury, which can occur in conditions such as acute tubular necrosis, toxic injury, or ischaemic damage to the kidneys.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Epithelial casts contain intact renal tubular cells and indicate acute tubular injury","Urinary casts form when proteins precipitate within renal tubules, trapping cellular elements","Different types of urinary casts help diagnose specific kidney conditions based on their contents and appearance"],"references":["Dvanajscak Z, Cossey LN, Larsen CP. A practical approach to the pathology of renal intratubular casts. Semin Diagn Pathol. 2020 May;37(3):127-134. doi: 10.1053/j.semdp.2020.02.001. Epub 2020 Feb 14. PMID: 32147230.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. 